File: South Africa's Zubayr Hamza (R) plays a shot as Netherlands' Scott Edwards (L) looks on during the first one-day international (ODI) cricket match between South Africa and the Netherlands at SuperSport Park in Centurion on November 26, 2021. PHILL MAGAKOE / AFP JOHANNESBURG - Proteas batsman Zubayr Hamza has tested positive for a prohibited substance, under the International Cricket Council's anti-doping controls. Cricket South Africa has announced that Hamza is not disputing the positive test and that he's fully cooperating with the ICC. The test batsman has also agreed to a voluntary suspension, while written submissions are being sent to the world governing body. READ: Proteas out to tame Tigers The positive test is for a substance called Furosemide, which is not performance-enhancing. According to CSA, Hamza was able to explain how it entered his system. He has withdrawn from the Proteas squad ahead of the Bangladesh series. Proteas batter Zubayr Hamza is cooperating fully with the ICC after testing positive for a prohibited substance.
